:1,"category":"family","header":"Father's silk cap — used at Fletcher's baptism","body":"His father Rev. Roger Newton's 1683 will bequeathed him a silk cap 'for a child' — written before any child was born. The cap was used approximately eighteen months later at the baptism of his son Fletcher on January 15, 1685. The will anticipated a family that had not yet arrived."},{"number":2,"category":"death","header":"Wife died the day before him","body":"Abigail died April 18, 1690 in Milford; Roger died April 19 — one day later, aged about 42. Both are buried in the Milford Cemetery. Their children Fletcher and Mary were five years old and not yet two."}],"quotes":[],"research_sources":[],"artworks":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Roger Newton Jr.","first_name":"Roger","last_name":"Newton","suffix":"Jr.","married_names":[]},"documents":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"roger-newton-jr-1648"},"I00009":{"id":"I00009","classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"descent_paths_to_thomas":0,"is_progenitor":false},"birth":{"year":1652,"month":6,"day":13,"city":"Milford","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"parents":{"father_research_notes":"John Fletcher of Milford, Connecticut"},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"H00012","children_ids":["H00047","H00048"],"marriage_number":1,"location_country":"United States"}],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entry 12"}],"gender":"female","tags":[],"number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"death":{"year":1690,"month":4,"day":18,"city":"Milford","county":"New Haven","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"baptism":{"year":1652,"month":6,"day":13,"city":"Milford","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM005","plot_notes":"Milford Cemetery. FindAGrave confirms burial."},"cross_connections":[],"is_placeholder":false,"former_ids":[],"residence":{"country":"United States"},"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"research_tags":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"death","header":"Died one day before her husband","body":"Abigail died April 18, 1690 in Milford; Roger died April 19. Both were in their early forties. Their children Fletcher and Mary were five years old and not yet two."}],"quotes":[],"research_sources":[],"artworks":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Abigail Fletcher Newton","first_name":"Abigail","last_name":"Newton","married_names":["Newton"],"maiden_name":"Fletcher"},"documents":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"abigail-fletcher-1652"},"X00076":{"id":"X00076","classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":true},"birth":{"year":1649,"month":4,"day":1,"city":"Milford","county":"New Haven","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1703,"month":11,"day":10,"city":"Milford","county":"New Haven","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"X00077","date_year":1680,"location_city":"Milford","location_county":"New Haven","location_state":"Connecticut","location_country":"United States","end_type":"death","end_year":1703,"children_ids":["I00064","I00021"]}],"sources":[{"short":"Families of Early Milford","notes":"Joseph Platt entry confirms children Hannah (m. Fletcher Newton) and Phebe (m. Samuel Newton)"},{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entries 41, 47"}],"parents":{"father_id":"X00098","mother_id":"X00099"},"gender":"male","tags":["milford_founder","politician"],"number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"baptism":{"year":1649,"month":4,"day":1,"city":"Milford","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Two daughters each married a Newton first cousin","body":"His daughters Phebe and Hannah both married into the Newton family of Milford — Phebe to Samuel Newton, Hannah to Samuel's first cousin Fletcher Newton. Two Platt sisters from the same household, two Newton cousins. Joseph was himself the son of Deacon Richard Platt, one of Milford's founding settlers."},{"number":2,"category":"character","header":"At dead of night he and his friends","body":"In 1671, young Joseph Platt and companions George Clark, Joseph Northrup, and Samuel Clark destroyed the Wepawaug Indians' fort \"with the utmost secrecy, at dead of night.\" The fort was probably vacant. They were tried before the General Court at New Haven, each fined £10, and ordered to rebuild what they had torn down."},{"number":3,"category":"military","header":"Lieutenant of the Milford Train Band, 1698","body":"Trainbands were the basic colonial militia unit — periodic training companies from which fighting forces were selected. He was Lieutenant of the Eldest Train Band at Milford in October 1698, and was elected Deputy from Milford to the Connecticut General Assembly in May 1700."},{"number":4,"category":"legacy","header":"No will — his son Joseph administered","body":"No will of Joseph is on record. His inventory was taken March 21, 1703/4. His widow Mary and son Joseph were appointed administrators, though the son was still a minor at the time."}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"civic_peer","related_id":"X00096","display_label":"Both destroyed the Wepawaug fort — fined £10.","link_text":"John Fowler"}],"bio":{"display_name":"Joseph Platt","first_name":"Joseph","last_name":"Platt","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"joseph-platt-1649"},"X00077":{"id":"X00077","classification":{"include_in_path_calcu